# Subagent Dispatch Policy

This repo defines specialist subagents under `.cursor/agents/**/*.md`. Each
file has YAML frontmatter (`name` + `description`) describing the agent and
when to use it. Cursor itself orchestrates them via the Task tool — there is
no JSON protocol and no separate orchestrator agent. This rule **is** the
dispatch policy.

**Your job as the primary agent:** for every non-trivial task, decide which
subagents to dispatch, in what order, and what can run in parallel. Do not
implement specialist work inline when a matching subagent exists.

---

## 1. Agent Catalog (capability + write-permission)

Treat `read-only` as **safe to parallelize**, and `write-capable` as **must be
serialized** unless file-set isolation is proven (see §3).

The catalog below is the **complete, authoritative list** of subagents that
exist in `.cursor/agents/`. Do not reference agents outside this list.

### Read-only / advisory agents (parallel-safe by default)

| Agent | Path | Use for |
|---|---|---|
| `explorer` | `.cursor/agents/explorer/explorer.md` | Repository discovery — finding files, entry points, modules, references, prior art |
| `backend-architect` | `.cursor/agents/architectures/backend-architect.md` | Server-side system design, API contracts, layering, data flow, integration (advisory, no edits) |
| `frontend-architect` | `.cursor/agents/architectures/frontend-architect.md` | Client-side architecture, composition model, state ownership, data fetching, performance topology, a11y topology (advisory, no edits) |
| `ui-ux-designer` | `.cursor/agents/designers-stilist/ui-ux-designer.md` | UX research framing, IA, journeys, layout, **component specs across all states**, microcopy, motion, design-system stewardship, **WCAG / keyboard / ARIA / contrast** review (single agent covering UI + UX + accessibility) |
| `architect-reviewer` | `.cursor/agents/reviewers/architect-reviewer.md` | Architecture quality review, coupling, scalability risk, evolution debt |
| `code-reviewer` | `.cursor/agents/reviewers/code-reviewer.md` | Correctness, maintainability, performance, test-quality review |
| `security-reviewer` | `.cursor/agents/reviewers/security-reviewer.md` | OWASP-style audit, secrets, authn/authz, input handling, dependency risk, agent/MCP/instruction surfaces |
| `database-reviewer` | `.cursor/agents/reviewers/database-reviewer.md` | SQL, migrations, indexing, RLS, concurrency, Postgres-specific review |

### Write-capable agents (serialize by default)

| Agent | Path | Owns |
|---|---|---|
| `backend-developer` | `.cursor/agents/coding-agents/backend-developer.md` | Server-side code, APIs, services, data layer, auth, queues, observability |
| `frontend-developer` | `.cursor/agents/coding-agents/frontend-developer.md` | UI implementation, components, hooks, state, data fetching, performance, SSR / RSC, concurrent React features (covers React 18+ depth) |
| `refactor-cleaner` | `.cursor/agents/spesific/refactor-cleaner.md` | Cleanup, dead-code removal, structural simplification, post-feature hardening |

> If a capability you need (e.g. dedicated planner, docs lookup, websocket
> engineer, test automator, documentation engineer) is not in this catalog,
> **do the work inline using Cursor's built-in tools** (Plan mode for
> planning, WebFetch / WebSearch for docs, etc.) — do not invent a subagent
> that doesn't exist on disk.

---

## 2. Parallelism rules for READ-ONLY agents

**Rule R1 — MUST parallelize independent reads.**
If two or more read-only agents are needed and **none of them depends on
another's output**, you MUST dispatch them in a single message (parallel Task
calls). Sequential dispatch of independent read work is a defect.

Examples of mandatory parallel patterns:

- `explorer` (find files in backend slice) + `explorer` (find files in
  frontend slice) — independent.
- `code-reviewer` + `security-reviewer` + `architect-reviewer` on the same diff — independent.
- `ui-ux-designer` reviewing a screen + `code-reviewer` reviewing the implementation — independent.
- `backend-architect` (or `frontend-architect`) design proposal + `explorer` (find existing patterns) — independent.

**Rule R2 — Serialize only on real data dependency.**
A read agent runs *after* another only if it literally needs the previous
agent's output. Examples:

- `architect-reviewer` after `backend-architect` or `frontend-architect` when reviewing the proposed design.
- `ui-ux-designer` after `frontend-architect` when the design spec must conform to the chosen composition model and state ownership (see §4).
- `code-reviewer` after a write agent finishes.

If you cannot name the data dependency in one sentence, the work is independent
and MUST be parallel.

---

## 3. Parallelism rules for WRITE-CAPABLE agents

**Rule W1 — Default is strictly sequential (≈99% of the time).**
Dispatch write-capable agents one at a time, with explicit handoffs.

**Rule W2 — Parallel writes are allowed ONLY when file-set isolation is proven.**
You may parallelize two write agents in a single message only if **all** of
these are true:

1. You have already run `explorer` (or otherwise enumerated the file scope).
2. Each agent owns a **disjoint, explicit file set**.
3. Neither agent will create, rename, move, or delete files outside its own set.
4. Neither agent edits a shared config, lockfile, root package manifest,
   barrel/index file, schema file, or anything imported by the other's scope.
5. You give each agent its file allowlist in the dispatch prompt and forbid
   touching anything else.

If any of the five fails, **serialize**.

**Rule W3 — When in doubt, serialize.**
The cost of sequential writes is small. The cost of two writers stomping the
same file is a broken commit. Bias to serial.

**Rule W4 — Mixed read+write is allowed.**
A write agent may run in parallel with read-only agents *as long as* the read
agents do not depend on the write agent's output. Example: while
`backend-developer` implements an endpoint, an `explorer` pass on an
unrelated module can run in parallel.

---

## 4. Mandatory triggers

These are not optional. If the trigger is hit, the agent runs.

- **Repository scanning / unfamiliar code area** → dispatch `explorer` first.
  Do not start implementation, review, or planning on an unknown surface
  without an `explorer` pass. `explorer` may run in parallel with other
  independent reads.

- **Planning is needed** (multi-step, ambiguous, cross-cutting, or user asks
  for a plan) → use Cursor's built-in **Plan mode** (`SwitchMode` to `plan`).
  Do not invent ad-hoc plans inline for non-trivial tasks. There is no
  dedicated planner subagent in this repo.

- **Architecture-level change** (new module boundary, new integration, broad
  refactor) → `backend-architect` and/or `frontend-architect` (pick by area,
  run in parallel if both apply) **before** implementation, `architect-reviewer`
  **after**.

- **Frontend component / UI feature work** → see §4a (mandatory chain).

- **After any write phase on non-trivial code** → dispatch `code-reviewer`.
  Add `security-reviewer` if the change touches auth, input handling, secrets,
  or external I/O. Add `database-reviewer` if SQL/migrations/RLS changed.
  These reviewers run **in parallel** (independent read work — Rule R1).

### 4a. Frontend component development chain (MANDATORY)

Whenever a **new frontend component is being designed or built**, or an
existing component is **substantially redesigned** (new states, new variants,
new responsive behavior, new accessibility model, or new interaction model),
you MUST follow this serialized chain:

```
explorer  →  frontend-architect  →  ui-ux-designer  →  frontend-developer  →  code-reviewer ∥ ui-ux-designer (spec/a11y conformance)
```

Why this order is mandatory:

1. **`frontend-architect` first** decides *where* the component lives in the
   composition model, *who* owns its state, *what* its data contract is, and
   *how* it fits the performance / a11y topology of the app. This is an
   architectural decision and must be made before visual or interaction
   design begins.

2. **`ui-ux-designer` next, after the architect's decision** turns that
   architectural decision into an implementation-ready UI/UX specification:
   layout, all visual states (default / hover / focus / active / disabled /
   loading / empty / error / success), responsive behavior, microcopy,
   motion, **and the WCAG / keyboard / ARIA model**. The designer works
   *within* the boundaries the architect set (composition slot, state
   ownership, data contract) — it does not redesign the architecture.

3. **`frontend-developer` implements** strictly against both outputs: the
   architect's contract and the designer's spec.

4. **Post-implementation** `code-reviewer` and `ui-ux-designer` run **in
   parallel** — `code-reviewer` for correctness/maintainability/perf, and
   `ui-ux-designer` for spec-conformance and a11y conformance.

Exceptions (chain may be shortened, never reordered):

- **Trivial cosmetic tweak** to an existing component (e.g. spacing nudge,
  copy fix, color token swap) with no new states or interaction changes →
  `frontend-developer` only, then `code-reviewer`.
- **Pure refactor** of an existing component with no behavior change →
  `refactor-cleaner` → `code-reviewer`.
- **Architecture is already settled** for this slice (recent ADR, recent
  `frontend-architect` pass) → may skip `frontend-architect` and start at
  `ui-ux-designer`, but document the decision being relied on.
- **Design system primitive** (token, base primitive) → still follow the
  full chain; the architect decides the contribution boundary, the designer
  owns the spec.

Never skip `ui-ux-designer` to "save time" on a real component. Accessibility
and state design are not post-hoc concerns — they belong in the spec, before
code is written.

